{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"72c41d3c-ed59-40bd-a1cf-c996f0d2ee19","content":"Here's my analysis:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe developer report confirms the overhead is **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation**, not compilation. This is the key difference:\n\n- **Visual Studio** keeps MSBuild nodes alive in-process — evaluation results are cached across builds.\n- **`dotnet build` CLI** spawns a new MSBuild process each invocation and sets `/nodeReuse:false` by default, so nothing is cached between runs.\n\n## Recommendations (most impactful first)\n\n### 1. Enable the MSBuild Server (biggest win)\n\nSet this environment variable to keep an MSBuild server process alive between CLI builds — directly mirroring what VS does:\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\n\nOr add to the project:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <MSBuildServer>true</MSBuildServer>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nThis avoids the cold-start penalty on every `dotnet build` invocation.\n\n### 2. Use `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\nThis keeps MSBuild resident and rebuilds on file changes — no repeated startup cost at all.\n\n### 3. Upgrade to .NET 9+\n\n.NET 9 enables **Terminal Build Acceleration** by default, which makes the MSBuild server the default behavior for CLI builds. If upgrading is feasible, change `TargetFramework` to `net9.0` and the problem largely disappears.\n\n### 4. Enable Node Reuse\n\nBy default, `dotnet build` passes `/nodeReuse:false`. Override it:\n\n```bash\nexport MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=0\n```\n\nThis keeps MSBuild worker nodes alive between builds, reducing startup time for subsequent invocations.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The project and code are fine — the bottleneck is the CLI's default behavior of discarding MSBuild processes after each build. Enabling the MSBuild server (`DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`) is the single highest-impact fix, and `dotnet watch build` is ideal for rapid edit-build cycles.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2611078c-6f2d-4ae7-b62a-7870a11e12b0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow (2-4 seconds) for incremental builds even when nothing has changed, while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've verified analyzers aren't the issue and incremental build targets work correctly.\n\nThe key insight here is the difference between how Visual Studio and CLI builds work:\n\n1. **Visual Studio** keeps the MSBuild process running in the background (MSBuild server/node reuse), so project evaluation is cached and process startup is amortized.\n\n2. **`dotnet build` from CLI** spawns a new MSBuild process each time by default, incurring:\n   - .NET SDK/runtime startup cost\n   - MSBuild node startup\n   - Full project graph re-evaluation\n\nThe main solutions are enabling the MSBuild server (available in .NET 8+ via `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`) to keep a persistent process between builds, or enabling node reuse by setting `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=0` to allow MSBuild to cache nodes across invocations instead of tearing them down after each build.\n\nI could also leverage `dotnet watch` for the development loop to avoid repeated startup costs, use graph-based builds for multi-project solutions, or in .NET 9+ take advantage of Terminal Build Acceleration which caches evaluation through the MSBuild server. For .NET 8 specifically, the MSBuild server is probably the most impactful change since it directly addresses the startup overhead that dominates incremental build times. The real bottleneck here is MSBuild startup overhead rather than compilation itself, so project-level tweaks won't move the needle much. The practical solutions are using `dotnet watch build` to keep the process alive between builds, enabling the MSBuild server with `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`, or upgrading to .NET 9 which has built-in Terminal Build Acceleration. For this particular project, I should focus on the most impactful recommendation. I should organize this into a clear structure: first explaining why the CLI is slow compared to Visual Studio, then laying out the practical fixes at both the project and environment level.","outputTokens":1698,"requestId":"D815:3D7DF2:6A975F6:72E673D:6A03CC51"},"id":"77bbc17e-5db6-450e-affb-763a7790fcfe","timestamp":"2026-05-13T00:57:24.121Z","parentId":"e38756c8-f629-46cd-9690-f40bddf3ace6"}
